05353nam a22008655i 9783110928341DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20132004gw     fo  d z      ger d  a(OCoLC)1013937112  a97831109283417 a10.1515/97831109283412doi  a(DE-B1597)45704  a(OCoLC)853251380  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 ager  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aHistorische Semantik in den romanischen Sprachen /chrsg. von Franz Lebsanft, Martin-Dietrich Gleßgen.  aReprint 2013 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2013] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistische Arbeiten ,x0344-6727 ;v4830 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNeuere Entwicklungen der Linguistik verleihen der historischen Semantik innovative Impulse. Für die romanistische Wortforschung ist der Moment gekommen, Sprachtheoretiker und -historiker miteinander ins Gespräch zu bringen. Soweit die strukturalistische Semantik in kognitive Konzepte der historischen Semantik integriert wird, bleibt sie für die lexikalische Analyse älterer Sprachstufen attraktiv und für die Linguistik des Bedeutungswandels relevant. Kognitive Modelle erfahren neue Akzentuierungen in Richtung auf eine pragmatische historische Semantik, die für sprachhistorische Fragen besonders offen ist.  aRecent developments of linguistics have given innovative impulses to historical semantics. For the Romance study of words, the time has come to establish a dialogue between theorists and historians of language. As far as structural semantics are integrated into cognitive concepts of historical semantics, it remains attractive for the lexical analysis of older language levels and relevant for the linguistics of semantic change/change in meaning. Cognitive models are undergoing new accentuations towards a pragmatic historical semantics, which are open to/receptive to language-historical questions in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aRomance languagesxSemanticsvCongresses. 4aHistorische Semantik. 4aKongress. 4aMünchen ‹2001›. 4aRomanische Sprachen. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBernhard, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorn, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleßgen, Martin-Dietrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleßgen, Martin-Dietrich, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGsell, Otto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleiber, Georges, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Franz-Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLebsanft, Franz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLebsanft, Franz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMihatsch, Wiltrud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMutz, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMähren, Frankwalt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfister, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiegel, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrott, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStädtler, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThibault, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVölker, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo